\chapter{Collective Action}
\label{chap:government}
%#############################################################
% \epigraph{The truth about a city's aspirations isn't found in its vision. 
% It's found in its budget.}{Brent Toderian}
\epigraph{Show me the incentive and I will show you the outcome}{Charlie Munger}

The final two chapters of this book discuss actions
that can be taken by \textbf{collectives} (this chapter) and
\textbf{individuals} (Chapter~\ref{chap:personal_action})
to live more sustainably.
The purpose of the final two chapters
is to provide a breadth of possible actions to stimulate creative thinking and
meaningful action among readers, 
both as members of collectives and as individuals.
Necessarily, little depth is provided on any single action.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Sentences for sustainability}
\label{sec:sentences_for_sustainability}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

The collective and individual actions for sustainability 
are constructed as \emph{sentences} for sustainability, 
each with 
a subject, 
a verb, and 
an object.
The subjects are sustainability actors. 
The verbs are sustainability actions.
The objects are arenas in which the sustainability actions can take place.
Sustainability sentences look like this:

\begin{equation}
\label{eq:Sent4Sust}
\small
\begin{tabular}{ccccc}
  $\text{ACTOR}$    & + & $\text{ACTION}$        & + & $\text{ARENA .}$
\end{tabular}
\normalsize
\end{equation}


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Actors} 
\label{sec:actors_def}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

In sustainability sentences, 
the actors are individuals or collectives who perform the action.
The topic of this chapter is collective actions toward sustainability.
Collective actions are appropriate for problems that are ``too big'' 
to be solved by a single person.
Collective actions often require the cooperation of several groups to be successful.
In this chapter, we consider collective sustainability actions taken by
\textbf{governments}, \textbf{corporations}, and \textbf{organizations}.
The next chapter considers sustainability actions taken by individuals.


%..............................
\paragraph{Governments} 
\label{sec:collective_govt}
%..............................

The first type of collective group 
{has the power to make laws, rules, and policies.
We call this type governments.
Governments exist at local, regional, national, and international levels.
Governmental organizations can have very narrow and specific responsibilities 
(like a local zoning board)
or broad and general responsibilities 
(like state or national legislatures).
Governments can cooperate with each other in many ways, 
such as international treaties, the International Monetary Fund, and 
cost-sharing agreements between state and federal agencies for road construction.


%..............................
\paragraph{Corporations}
\label{sec:collective_corp}
%..............................

The second type of collective group is business corporations. 
Examples include Volkswagen, Siemens Gamesa Renewable Energy,
the Saudi Arabian Oil Company\index{Saudi Arabian Oil Company}, Maersk\index{Maersk}, and Best Buy\index{Best Buy}.
Characteristically, corporations are engaged in commercial activity, 
that is, {making and selling products and services.
A business can be ``for profit,'' like Apple, Amazon, or Johnson and Johnson, or
``not for profit,'' like the Educational Testing Service, the Mayo Clinic, World 
Vision International, and most colleges and universities.
Often, charitable foundations are structured as business corporations. 
For example, the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation is a charitable foundation
with a corporate structure.

Some U.S.\ states allow alternative corporate charters that blend the for-profit
and not-for-profit corporate structures.
A benefit corporation is an example of this blended structure.
It is a for-profit company that also attempts to benefit society, its workers,
its community and/or the environment in addition to making a profit. 
Because this benefit is part of the corporate charter, it is the fiduciary 
responsibility of company officers to consider these other stakeholders 
beyond merely maximizing shareholder value.  


%..............................
\paragraph{Organizations} 
\label{sec:collective_org}
%..............................

The third type of collective group is called, generically, organizations.
Example organizations include the 
American Society of Heating, Refrigerating, and Air-conditioning Engineers 
(ASHRAE)\index{American Society of Heating, Refrigerating, and Air-conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE)},
the 3$^{\text{rd}}$ Generation Partnership Project (3GPP),
local churches, the Internet Society, political
parties, environmental organizations, and community and civic groups.
A distinguishing characteristic of organizations is voluntary association,
meaning that individuals choose to be a member of the organization.

Collectives sometimes straddle the boundaries between categories.
For instance, the Federal National Mortgage Association (``Fannie Mae'') is a
U.S.\ government sponsored business corporation.
Many nonprofits mix a business corporate structure with a voluntary organization(s).
For example, the Roman Catholic Church is an association of corporate entities
(such as Catholic Relief Services) and
organizations (including local parishes).
Another example is the National Audubon Society,
which is a company affiliated with
nearly five hundred local, independent chapters.
Lastly, the Internet Society (mentioned above)
is an organization that sets policy for high-level internet activities; 
it is quasi-governmental in nature.

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
Despite some ``fuzziness'' in the different types of collectives,
the categories are useful as a framework to help us think about the capabilities
of collectives. 
Not all collectives are equally suited for or adept at a given task.
\end{mcframe}


%..............................
\paragraph{Individuals} 
\label{sec:individuals_def}
%..............................

Individuals are persons who are committed to sustainability and
take actions that match their commitments;
see Chapter~\ref{chap:personal_action}.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Actions} 
\label{sec:actions_def}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

In both this chapter (collective actions) and the next (individual actions), 
we consider four types of sustainability actions:
choices, laws, research, and education.
The four types of actions are not exhaustive of all possible actions, 
but they provide a framework
to guide our thinking about possible sustainability actions. 


%..............................
\paragraph{Choices} 
\label{sec:actions_choices}
%..............................

Individually and collectively, we have many opportunities to live more sustainably.
Sometimes we just need to pick the most sustainable option in a given
situation or context. 
The decisions might be large (where to live, family planning) 
or small (paper vs.\ plastic bags).
It might be a single, simple choice or a lifestyle-related choice (driving vs.\ walking).

Characteristic of the ``choice'' action is that it has a direct impact on sustainability, and
it involves choosing a sustainable option from a menu of existing activities or products.
Nothing new needs to be invented.


%..............................
\paragraph{Laws}
\label{sec:actions_law}
%..............................

Laws and regulations \href{https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/affect}{affect}
(and sometimes define and sometimes \href{https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/effect#Verb}{effect})
relationships among individuals, 
collectives (such as unions and religious organizations), 
corporations, 
markets, and
the natural world (for example, plants, animals, inanimate things, and energy resources).
In some cases, laws and regulations define what cannot be done.  
For example, some types of pollution\index{pollution}, such as dumping oil in waterways, are prohibited.
In other cases, laws and regulations define what must be done.
For example, renewable energy portfolio standards mandate that a certain percentage 
of electricity must come from renewables\index{renewable electricity}.
In still other cases, governments pass laws and regulations 
to define how things must be done.
For example, regulations can establish markets for carbon trading.
Laws and regulations are not neutral; 
they affect relationships on many levels.
As such, laws and regulations can be seen as interventions in societal systems.
Changes in those relationships have sustainability implications.

Changing laws and regulations (the ``rules of the game'')
can provide widespread incentives
to encourage self-interested individuals to become more sustainable.
To extend the ``menu'' metaphor, if choice actions involve selecting a product or 
service from an existing menu, rules and regulations change the prices
of the menu items. 
In turn, the prices change the behavior and choices of both collectives and individuals.

Often the purpose of these rules and regulations is to internalize externalities\index{negative externality}.
The rules of the game are exceedingly important for the environment, 
because unintended environmental consequences often emerge from
financial incentives that accompany laws and regulations.
A classic example of unintended consequences is the 
tragedy of the commons\index{tragedy of the commons}\index{commons!tragedy of the}.
The tragedy of the commons describes situations when
a resource is owned by no one---or by everyone. 
Because no one individually owns the benefits of conserving the resource, 
self-interested behavior results in little concern for sustainability.
When enough people can extract the resource, 
the outcome is consumption so great that the resource can be destroyed,
leading to reduced welfare for the group and,
if the resource is ``natural,''
environmental collapse.

A ``commons'' can emerge any time there is no controlling authority 
to set rules and regulations, manage resource extraction\index{resource extraction},
and preserve the resource.
The commons becomes tragic when the resource is depleted by overexploitation.
Controlling authorities are often absent for many environmental challenges
that are global in scope
(such as international fisheries\index{fisheries},
non-localized air pollution\index{pollution!air}, and greenhouse-gas\index{CO$_2$ emissions} pollution), 
because reaching international agreement 
to establish controlling authorities can be difficult.
Self-interested parties can use the political strategy of ``deregulation''
to weaken controlling authorities and
create a commons that can be (over) exploited for short-term financial gain.

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
Elinor Ostrum\index{Ostrum, Elinor} won the 2009 Nobel prize in economics 
for showing that tragedies of the commons 
can be avoided without top-down regulation or privatization of the resource
by prudent collaboration within strong societal structures. 
\end{mcframe}


%..............................
\paragraph{Research} 
\label{sec:actions_research}
%..............................

The ``research'' action means both the creation of new knowledge about sustainability and
the invention or development of new technology for sustainability.
For instance, forest and wildlife managers may wish to know how climate change\index{climate change} is
altering the range of the mountain pine beetle, which affects whitebark pine and 
grizzly bear\index{bear!grizzly} populations.
Or, a company may develop better designs for electric motors, batteries, or 
wind-turbine blades.
To extend the ``menu'' metaphor further, technological development adds new
(hopefully more sustainable) options to the menu. 
On the other hand, sustainability research gives more information about menu items,
like finding and reporting the number of calories in a hamburger.
New knowledge doesn't change the price on the menu (in dollars) but it might influence
your decision to purchase, anyway.
New knowledge created by sustainability research includes (for example) the ongoing 
scientific investigation of the mechanisms of climate change\index{climate change}, 
life-cycle analysis to determine the sustainability implications of paper versus
plastic shopping bags,
and the gathering of demographic and macroeconomic data.
% I'm commenting the next sentence, because it seems too obvious.
% Not all R\&D activities meet the definition of the research action; 
% for the purposes of this book, research has to be sustainability related. 

Laws and regulations intersect with research when governments support research 
in a number of ways.
Through patents,
those who develop sustainable tools can recoup their investment
by means of limited-time monopoly rights 
to sell that invention to others looking to become more sustainable. 
Governments also fund research. 
Some of this funding is direct,
as when governments employ scientists to develop models of the atmosphere\index{atmosphere}. 
Government grants support research by private entities, such as
sustainability-related research funded by the 
National Science Foundation\index{National Science Foundation (NSF)}. 
Occasionally, governments post a major prize for solving a hard problem. 
We could imagine the government establishing 
a prize for developing cost-effective carbon sequestration\index{carbon sequestration} technology.


%..............................
\paragraph{Education}
\label{sec:actions_education}
%..............................

Education has the power to change hearts and minds, and thus, the way people behave.
Disseminating information about sustainability is a crucial step in achieving a
sustainable society.
Education includes advertising, public service announcements, reading books for a term paper,
creating a website, and making or watching a documentary film.
Characteristics of the education action include the acquisition or dissemination
of existing knowledge about sustainability.
Simply going to school or getting a degree does not count as the education action
in the context of this book, 
unless that education is sustainability-related.
In our menu metaphor, education is like advertising. 
You want consumers to know about what's on the menu. 
You might point out special deals or combos.

A typical sequence of actions might look something like this: 
a scientist discovers new aspects of climate change\index{climate change} (research), 
the news media reports the problem (education),
the government creates incentives to change behavior (law), 
companies respond by developing alternative products and services (research again), and 
consumers respond by buying the new, more sustainable option (choice).


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Arenas} 
\label{sec:arenas_def}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

In this chapter and the next, 
we consider sustainability actions undertaken in arenas
corresponding to eight previous chapters:
population, 
affluence, 
resources, 
impacts, 
households, 
transportation, 
agriculture, and 
land use. 


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Collective sentences for sustainability}
\label{sec:collective_sentences_for_sustainability}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

In this section, sustainability sentences are 
presented in the order of sustainability arenas
corresponding to Chapters~\ref{chap:population}--\ref{chap:land_use_urban_planning}.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Population~\Pparen{}}
\label{sec:collective_population}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

As shown in Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}
and in Figure~\ref{fig:PopulationGraph}, 
rising population~\Pparen{} is a driver for environmental impacts~\Iparen{}. 
Slowing or reversing population growth would reduce environmental impacts,
all other things being equal.


%..............................
\paragraph{Government+Choice+Population}
%..............................

State and local governments are the entities in the U.S.\
and around the world that provide much or most of the education offered to citizens.
Providing general education to citizens, especially girls and women, 
is a seemingly effective way to reduce birthrates, slow population growth, and
reduce family size.
(Education is a ``choice'' for government because it is on the menu of things that 
they already do.
Governments can choose to expand access to education or enhance educational
opportunities, for instance, by building new schools, providing more scholarships,
or expanding to a year-round academic calendar.)
Another choice governments can make is to supply birth control technology
(oral contraceptives, symptom-thermal training, and condoms, for example)
to citizens to reduce population growth rates.


%..............................
\paragraph{Government+Education+Population}
%..............................

In addition, education for family planning can be done by governments.
Governments can disseminate information around family planning and birth control
to citizens, especially girls and women, to reduce population growth. 
(In contrast to the general education mentioned in the previous paragraph,
here specific training on birth control is counted as the education action 
because it has a direct sustainability effect on the target of the action, in this
case, on population.)


%..............................
\paragraph{Government+Law+Population}
%..............................

Government policies can have an effect on population.
For example, legislatures can pass laws
on number of children, incentives for having children, 
tax breaks for raising children, or direct payments to children
to affect the number of children per person
(often with unintended consequences). 
Lawmakers can also 
write family-friendly policies and 
establish programs such as 
generous maternity leave, early childhood education and daycare, 
health insurance, and subsidized college tuition
to affect birth rates. 


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Affluence~\Aparen{}}
\label{sec:collective_affluence}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX} and Figure~\ref{fig:AffluenceGraph-Nordhaus}
shows that rising affluence~\Aparen{}
drives larger environmental impacts~\Iparen{}. 
Ironically, the purpose of many government actions 
is to produce ever-rising levels of affluence, 
because citizens who are becoming more affluent 
are likely to retain their current political leaders and their current political system.
To become more sustainable, we need to encourage lower economic growth rates and less consumption,
especially among already-wealthy citizens and in already-wealthy countries.
Taken further, the degrowth movement\index{degrowth!as a movement} seeks to find a way to 
wind down the economic system while retaining high standards
of human well-being among citizens; see Section~\ref{sec:circular_economy}.


%..............................
\paragraph{Government+Law+Affluence}
%..............................

National governments, 
international organizations, and
nongovernmental organizations
can tax environmental externalities\index{negative externality}
proportionally,
ensuring that those who cause the most environmental damage pay the most for remediation.
For the prime example of this book (energy and climate change\index{climate change}),
stiff carbon taxes\index{carbon tax} are a good way to penalize polluters,
minimize the economic impact on nonpolluting, often poorer, citizens, and
encourage carbon-free energy.


%..............................
\paragraph{Government+Education+Affluence}
%..............................

A mandatory carbon labeling scheme
(like nutrition labels)
could be implemented
to provide point-of-purchase information to consumers
about the relative carbon intensity of goods~\citep{Zhao_2012}.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Resource intensity of the economy~\Rparen{}}
\label{sec:collective_resources}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX} shows that
rising resource intensity of the economy~\Rparen{}
would drive environmental impacts~\Iparen{} upward.
However, Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyIntensityGraph-Nordhaus} shows that the 
world's economy has been reducing its resource (energy) intensity over time.
Of the four \mft{PARX} terms, resource intensity of the economy~\Rparen{} 
is the only term moving in a sustainable direction over the long term;
see Equation \ref{eq:IPARX_rate_with_numbers}.
To reduce environmental impacts, 
economies need to use even fewer resources 
and emit less pollution\index{pollution} per dollar of GDP.


%..............................
\paragraph{Government+Law+Resources}
%..............................

Policies that encourage industrial energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} 
will reduce the energy required to generate a dollar of GDP
at the location of the energy use.
However, the rebound effect\index{rebound effect} and energy-efficiency\index{energy efficiency} 
backfire\index{backfire} can counteract energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} measures;
see Section~\ref{sec:rebound_effect}.
If the cost savings associated with a specific energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} intervention
are reinvested for growth (as most businesses do), 
the resulting increase in energy consumption from the expanded business
can reduce or (in the case of backfire\index{backfire}) eliminate the local energy savings
caused by the energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} measure. 
The net result is reduced total energy savings across the economy and, in the case of backfire\index{backfire},
increased total energy consumption.

To reduce rebound\index{rebound effect} or backfire\index{backfire}, 
schools and businesses can implement green revolving funds\index{green revolving fund},
wherein cost savings from energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} are used exclusively 
for additional energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency}.
By cutting off rebound\index{rebound effect}, 
green revolving funds can render energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} more effective
rather than ineffective.
At a larger scale, governments can develop green revolving funds
to provide resources for businesses and individuals to perform energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency} upgrades
and to which proceeds of those upgrades are paid.  

Introducing policies to make resources more expensive will 
increase incentives to use resources more efficiently.
If higher resource prices mean that more resources are left in the ground, 
future generations will have more resources to consume (or not),
thereby extending the life of reserves and increasing the likelihood that a 
weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} criterion is achieved;
see Section~\ref{sec:strong_weak_sust}.
Interestingly, more-expensive energy resources (especially oil)
tend to also reduce affluence~\Aparen{}~\cite{Hamilton:2009ui},
thereby further helping toward environmental sustainability\index{environmental sustainability}.

To reduce the extraction rate of natural resources, 
manufacturer takeback of all goods and 
widespread recycling\index{recycling} can be mandated. 
Recycling\index{recycling} metals, especially rare-earth metals is essential
to achieve weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} (at least).

A structural approach to reducing the resource intensity of economic activity~\Rparen{}
is to transition away from a production-based economy toward a service-based economy.
Providing services is less energy- and resource-insensitive than 
manufacturing.
That said, every economy, even a service-based economy, needs goods. 
Moving to a service-based economy carries risks that production is simply off-shored,
not eliminated altogether,
thereby increasing the resource intensity of a different economy.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Impact of resources~\Xparen{}}
\label{sec:collective_impact_intensity}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX} shows that reducing 
the impact of resources~\Xparen{}
will cause environmental impacts~\Iparen{} to decline.


%..............................
\paragraph{Government+Law+Impact intensity}
%..............................

One way to reduce the impact of resources~\Xparen{}
is to strengthen environmental regulations 
at both extraction\index{resource extraction} and disposal lifecycle stages.
At the extraction stage,
stricter regulations on tailings, emissions, and aqueous contamination
can be effective for reducing environmental degradation
in the mining, fishing, and forestry sectors.
At the disposal stage,
aggressive takeback policies can compel manufacturers 
to take responsibility (either financially or in practice)
for safe disposal of their products at end of life.
For example, one major source of ocean plastic pollution\index{pollution!plastic}
is discarded fishing nets. 
(See \ref{project:ocean_plastic}.)
An international treaty that banned discarding nets and added penalties for 
doing so could help to address the issue of ocean plastics\index{pollution!plastic}.

In lieu of mandating that manufacturers take back products, 
standards for ease of disassembly could be implemented.
In terms of the prime example (energy and CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions}),
governments can establish greenhouse gas\index{greenhouse gas} trading markets
to reduce emissions and encourage renewable energy adoption
with small economic impact.

To reduce CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!reduction}, 
governments can implement mandates for renewable energy generation~\cite{USEIA:2021tt}. 
Renewable mandates are 
usually expressed as a percentage of total energy generated and 
mostly applied to electricity\index{electricity}, not liquid fuels.
Renewable mandates are often called Renewable Portfolio Standards, 
mandating that electricity\index{electricity} producers have a certain fraction of 
electricity sales from renewable sources\index{renewable electricityg}.


%..............................
\paragraph{Corporations+Research+Impact intensity}
%..............................

When manufacturers are also responsible for disposal, 
disposal costs become an integral aspect of product design.
Manufacturers become incentivized to 
(a)~use fewer harmful substances in their products and
(b)~to make their products easier to recycle or remanufacture.

