\section{Summary}
\label{sec:collective_action_summary}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

This chapter looked at many ways to ``change the system''
to make the world more sustainable. 
It begins to answer the question,
``how could we reconfigure the systems and structures in our societies
to encourage and promote a more sustainable world?''

The examples of collective sustainability actions above 
are not exhaustive of all possible collective sustainability actions. 
(How could they be otherwise?)
The goal of this chapter is not to be exhaustive.
Rather, the goal is to be generative, 
to encourage readers to think of many additional ideas to become more sustainable.
Readers should explore options that fit local circumstances, 
always keeping in mind the global perspective provided 
by Chapters~\ref{chap:introduction}--\ref{chap:impact_intensity}.
Questions and problems at the end of the chapter assist the exploration process.

Astute readers will have noticed that governments are often 
the route by which collective actions are taken,
regulations are established, and laws are passed.
However, when politics and government enter the picture, 
winners and losers always emerge.
One or more groups benefit from political decisions
and one or more groups are disadvantaged by political decisions.
In that environment, 
self-interests and societal divisions impact political decisions, 
often making it difficult to respond effectively 
to intensifying sustainability challenges\index{sustainability challenges}. 
For example, the complete lack of any effective response to climate change\index{climate change}
by governments the world over 
shows the difficulties of mounting political responses to
sustainability challenges\index{sustainability challenges}.

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
Where governments are involved,
political problems must be solved before sustainability challenges\index{sustainability challenges}
can be addressed.
\end{mcframe}

Furthermore, decisions to become more sustainable often disadvantage 
entrenched business interests, 
because the current world is unsustainable.
For example, reducing CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!reduction}
disadvantages the entrenched fossil-fuel industry.
When that happens, entrenched interests can resist changes, 
hampering sustainability efforts.

That's not to say we shouldn't try to make collective change. 
Indeed, collective change is the only way to ensure that all people
(even those unaware of our sustainability challenges\index{sustainability challenges})
will live more sustainable lives.
But the barriers to collective action are high.

That said, governments consist of people.
In democracies, the people in government are chosen by the populace.
Thus, collective actions and personal action intertwine at elections
when representatives are selected.
Indeed, voting for representatives who favor collective change
toward sustainability 
is an important action that can be taken by individuals.
However, there are many more individual actions that can be undertaken
to move the world in a sustainable direction. 
Those individual actions are the subject of the next and final chapter.


